description: This dataset provides 28 years of environmental monitoring data (1995–2023) from 51 stations in the estuaries and coastal areas of the Basque Country in the Bay of Biscay. Covering 130 variables across water, sediments, and biota, it includes detailed records of phytoplankton, macroalgae, macroinvertebrates, and fish. Compiled in collaboration with the Basque Water Agency (URA), the dataset supports analysis of environmental responses to human pressures and management interventions, identifying patterns of environmental quality improvement within a context of natural variability. Provided in a FAIR² Data Package, the dataset is structured to ensure Findability, Accessibility, Interoperability, Reusability, and Artificial Intelligence-readiness, facilitated by structured metadata and Application Programming Interface access. This resource is intended for researchers and policymakers examining anthropogenic and natural influences on aquatic ecosystems, contributing to sustainable management, conservation practices, and alignment with European directives, including the Water Framework Directive.

dataArticle.name: Marine biodiversity and environmental data: an AI-ready, open dataset from the long term (1995–2023) monitoring network

step.name: Objective and Scope
step.description: The primary objective of this study was to assess environmental quality trends in the Basque Country’s marine ecosystems using long-term monitoring data from 1995 to 2023. Key areas of interest include examining water, sediment, and biological components to understand the impact of human pressures, such as industrial and urban discharges, as well as the effectiveness of management actions, like wastewater treatment. This dataset, gathered from 70 sampling stations across the Bay of Biscay, provides insights into environmental changes, supporting the overarching hypothesis that implemented management actions yield positive ecological effects.

step.name: Approach Overview
step.description: The study utilized an observational monitoring approach, gathering data over nearly three decades to facilitate trend analysis on ecosystem variables affected by anthropogenic and natural factors. Sampling followed standardized protocols for various ecosystems (water, sediment, and biota), as outlined by the Basque Water Agency (URA) and AZTI. Data collection methodologies, including EN 15972:2011 guidelines for water quality sampling, were consistently applied to enable cross-temporal and spatial comparisons. Detailed sampling protocols can be found in the URA resource portal: https://www.uragentzia.euskadi.eus/informacion/protocolos-de-muestreo-de-laboratorio-y-de-calculo-de-indices-y-metricas-para-el-seguimiento-del-estado-de-las-masas-de-agua-superficial-de-la-capv/webura00-01040102seguimiento/es/

step.name: Taxa Group and Sampling Protocols
step.description: Sampling methodologies were tailored to each group (taxagroup) to ensure accurate and representative data collection.

step.name: Instrumentation and References
step.description: Instruments such as van Veen grabs, CTD sensors, and beam trawls were utilized. Calibration and handling followed standardized protocols where available. Key references, including EN 15972:2011 and URA guidelines, were applied to ensure consistency. Detailed protocols are accessible at the URA resource portal: https://www.uragentzia.euskadi.eus/informacion/protocolos-de-muestreo-de-laboratorio-y-de-calculo-de-indices-y-metricas-para-el-seguimiento-del-estado-de-las-masas-de-agua-superficial-de-la-capv/webura00-01040102seguimiento/es/

step.name: Setup of Tools/Systems
step.description: Instrumentation and sampling setups varied by component, adhering to standardized protocols across water, sediment, and biota sampling.

step.name: Apply and document all additional calibration protocols.
step.description: Apply and document all additional calibration protocols.

step.name: CTD Calibration
step.description: The CTD sensor used in water sampling underwent regular calibration to ensure accuracy in measurements of dissolved oxygen, temperature, and salinity, following EN 15972:2011 protocols for water quality. Calibration details for sediment and biota equipment, such as the van Veen grab or beam trawl, were not documented in the provided information.

step.name: Sample Preparation
step.description: Sample preparation varied by component type, based on the specific parameter and storage requirements.

step.name: Sampling Frequency and Timing
step.description:
Sampling was conducted on the following schedules:
- **Water**: Quarterly, with some stations sampled at both high and low tides.
- **Sediments**: Annually, during January.
- **Phytoplankton** and Macroalgae: Quarterly.
- **Fish and Invertebrates**: Seasonal, aligned with site accessibility and species-specific behavior.

step.name: Temporal Data Logging
step.description: Collection dates (datecollected) were systematically recorded for all components to ensure robust temporal analyses.

step.name: Timing and Frequency
step.description: Data collection followed a consistent schedule, ensuring reliable comparisons over time.

step.name: Variables and Measurements
step.description: Explicitly measured variables were selected to provide a comprehensive view of environmental quality across components.

step.name: Data Logging and Monitoring
step.description:
Data logging procedures ensured systematic tracking for each component.
- Real-time logging was applied for immediate on-site measurements like temperature, dissolved oxygen, and pH. For sediment and biota samples, data were logged upon completion of laboratory analysis.
- The documentation did not specify whether data logging was performed manually or with automated systems. Information on specific data storage software or data logging methods was also not provided.

step.name: Processing of Data
step.description: Data processing involved multiple steps tailored to each component type to ensure consistency and accuracy.

step.name: Post-Processing
step.description: After initial processing, data underwent additional statistical analyses to assess long-term environmental trends across variables.

step.name: Analysis Techniques
step.description: A range of analytical techniques was used to provide robust time-series analyses across variables.

step.name: Quality Assurance Measures
step.description: Standardized sampling and analytical protocols were followed to ensure data consistency and accuracy.

step.name: Adjustment for High-Variability Variables
step.description: For variables cross-validated with independent datasets, statistical adjustments were applied to account for environmental variability. These adjustments aimed to refine the trend accuracy by minimizing the influence of natural fluctuations, providing a clearer view of anthropogenic effects.

step.name: Interpretation for High-Variability Variables
step.description: For variables without cross-validation, trends were interpreted with caution. For example, nutrient levels and sediment composition were analyzed with the understanding that observed changes might reflect natural environmental variability in addition to any anthropogenic influence.

step.name: Trend Robustness
step.description: To ensure trend reliability, non-parametric confidence intervals were calculated for each variable using the boot package in R. This approach applied bootstrap resampling to verify trend robustness, particularly for variables where natural variability could impact results.

varriableMeasured.value: We sample annually, always in winter (January to March). The van Veen grab (0.1 m2) is used in coastal  samples and the 0.03m2  van Veen grab is used for the estuarine sample E-A10. Each sample is frozen, until laboratory analysis.

varriableMeasured.name: top_10_freq
varriableMeasured.value:
description
We sample annually, always in winter (January to March). The van Veen grab (0.1 m2) is used in coastal  samples and the 0.03m2  van Veen grab is used for the estuarine sample E-A10. Each sample is frozen, until laboratory analysis.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            1
We sample annually, always in winter (January to March). A square of 0.5 x 0.5 m is used in intertidal estuarine samples. Each sample(15 cm depth) is conserved frozen, until laboratory analysis.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 1
We sample annually, always in autumn (October to December). Each sample is frozen, until laboratory analysis.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      1
We sample every three months (in few stations every month), collecting water at the surface with a Niskin bottle. See ISO for the standard sampling. For nutrients and contaminants                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                1
We sample every three months (in few stations every month), using a CTD for temperature, salinity, depth, irradiance, chlorophyll, light transmission, pH, dissolved oxygen                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        1
We sample in autumn (in most locations every three years in one every year), within three parts of each estuary (outer, middle, inner), with three hauls, uisng a trawl of 1.5 m wide beam trawl, net of 10 mm mesh size and 8 mm mesh size cod end; towed 10 min at 1.5 knots, in the smaller estuaries and one of 2.5 m wide beam trawl, net of 40 mm mesh size and 14 mm mesh size cod end; towed 10 min at 1.5 knots, in the larger one (Nerbioi). Although the element is "fish" we identify the demersal community, including fish and crustaceans. The species are identified onboard and released again    1
We sample annually, always in winter (January to March). The van Veen grab (0.1 m2) is used in coastal and estuarine samples which are subtidal. At each sampling station, three replicates are obtained and sieved through a mesh of 1 mm. The samples are conserved with formaldehide, until identification under a stereomicroscope                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             1
We sample annually, always in winter (January to March). A square of 0.5 x 0.5 m is used in estuarine samples which are intertidal. At each sampling station, three replicates are obtained (15 cm depth) and sieved through a mesh of 1 mm. The samples are conserved with formaldehide, until identification under a stereomicroscope                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            1
We sample in spring or early summer, every three years. Intertidal transects are placed in the coast and at different heights in the intertidal several quadrats are placed to study the composition and cover of macroalgae                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       1
We sample in spring or early summer, every three years. We cover the whole estuary, in the intertidal several, including quadrats to study the composition and cover of macroalgae                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 1
Name: count, dtype: int64
